    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Supports in form of animals' heads with one leg immediately below; used on tables and seats of the ancient world and revived in the late 18th and 19th centuries.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000020951/Ware and Stafford, Illustrated Dictionary of Ornament (1974)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Stutten in de vorm van dierenkoppen met één poot er direct onder. Gebruikt aan tafels en zittingen in de Oudheid en opnieuw in gebruik gebracht in de late 18e en 19e eeuw.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>其形式以動物頭部為柱頭，其下延伸出單足的支柱；在古代用於支撐桌子與座位，並重新流行於西元十八世紀晚期與十九世紀間。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
